list.item:
A Bee,
 from the AS Beo, Dan. Bi, Belg. Bie, Bye, Teut. Bien, C. Br. Baedd, Apicula, a little Bee. Mer. Caſ. derives it from the Lat. Apis; from hence, An Eat-Bee,
 a Bird ſo called, becauſe it feedeth upon Bees.

                       Book, from the AS. Boc, Fr. Th. Buoch, Dan. Bog, Teut. Buch, idem;
                        all, not unlikely,

from the AS. Bocce, a Beech-tree; becauſe the ancient Germans writ upon the barks of Beech-trees, inſtead of paper.

Bottle of hay,
 from the Fr. G. Boteau; or, for ought I know, corrupted from the Belg. Bondel, Teut. Bundtel; with us, A Bundle;
 which ſee.

Brunt, to bear the Brunt of the day;
 from the Teut. and Belg. Brunſt; (i. e.) the Heat of the day
 V. Burn.

To Bruſtle,
 from the AS. Brustlian, to ruſtle as Armour: Or as Dr. Th. H. ſagaciouſly divineth, q. d. To Briſtle,
 as an enraged boar.

Carreer, from the Fr. G. Carriere, Ital. Carriera, Hiſp. Carrera; as we ſay commonly, To ride in a full Carreer;
 from the Verb To Carry;
 which ſee.

Char-woman,
 from the Belg. Keeren; (i. e.)
 a woman hired to rub, and make clean the houſe.

Chard, The Chard of an Artechoke,
 from the Fr. G Chard, of the ſame ſignification. It may likewiſe come from the Lat. Carduus. Gardiners term that the Chard,
 that grows out of the roots of old Artechokes.

Chitterlings; Minſhew
 derives it from the Belg. Schyterlingh, in Eng. q. Shitterling;
 becauſe in them are contained the excrements. Yet I had rather draw it from the Teut. Kutteln, the inwards.

                       Clouterly-fellow,
                        from the Belg. Kloete, a ſtupid jolt-head: Or from Kluyte, Klouter,

thick; q. d. an unprofitable lump of fleſh.

Count, from the Fr. G. Comte, Conte, Ital. Conte; both from the Lat. Comes: From hence, A County;
 alſo, A Counteſs,
 from the Lat. barb. Comitiſſa, a Count's wife. This word is ſuppoſed to have crept into the Latin Tongue, in the time of Diocleſian, and to have ſignified, One of the King's Privy Council, becauſe he day by day accompanied the Emperor.

                       Craven, from the Verb To Crave; (i. e.) one that preſently asketh

pardon of an adverſary: Or from the AS. Creopan, to creep; q. d. one that falleth down at the feet of every one he has at any time offended: Or, q. d. Crave-hen;
                        that is, one addicted more to Venereal, than Marſhal affairs.

The Crown,
 from the Belg. Kruyne, idem;
 or the Fr. G. Coronne.

Crum, from the AS. Cruma, Teut. Krume, Krummel, id.
 from this laſt, To Crumble:
 They all flow from the Lat. Grumus, clots of any thing.

Cucking-ſtool;
 or rather, Ducking-ſtool; q. d. Choaking-ſtool;
 becauſe Scolds being thus puniſhed are almoſt ſtifled with water: V. Choke. Dr. Th. H. takes it from the Fr. G. Coquine, a Beggar-woman; becauſe ſturdy Beggar-women are waſhed in it.

To Dowſe,
 from the Belg. Douſen, idem;
 both from the Lat. Tunſare, to beat.

To Duck,
 from the Belg. and Teut. Ducken, idem:
 Or, from the AS. Gedufian, Ital. Tuffare, to dive.

To Fade,
 from the Belg. Vrdden, idem;
 and this from the Fr. G. Fade, impotent; alſo flat, unſavoury; all from the Lat. Vadere, to go; as we ſay, He is going, or gone.

Fennel; in Lincolnſhire, Finkel;
 by Aelfricus, Fynel;
 in Somnerus, Fenol;
 from the Teut. Fenchel, Fr. G. Fenouil, Ital. Finocchio; and all from the Lat. Foeniculum, an herb ſo called.

Flap of the ear,
 from the AS. Ear-laepƿe, or from the Verb To Flap;
 becauſe it is ſofter, and more eaſily moved than the reſt of the ear.

F
      •
   ea, from the AS. Flea, Belg. Vloo, Teut. Floh, idem;
 or perhaps from the Verb To Fly;
 becauſe ſhe leapeth ſo quickly, that ſhe may be thought to fly.

A Flounder,
 from the Dan. Flynder, idem;
 both not unlikely from the Lat. Fundulus; becauſe it moſtly abideth in the bottom of rivers.

                       The Freiſe,
                        a term in Architecture;

perhaps from the Fr. G. Fraiſe, a ruff. Evelin draws it from the Ital. Freggio, with us, A Fringe;
                        which ſee.

To Frisk,
 from the Ital. Frizzare, to skip about; and this from the Fr. G. Friſque, Freſh,
 and Brisk; both which ſee in their places.

A Fry,
 from the Fr. G. Fray, the ſpawn of fiſhes; and this from the Dan. Fraade, idem;
 alſo froth.

To Gad; Minſhew derives it from the Belg. Gaen, to Go;
 which ſee. It may alſo be drawn from the Teut. or rather, the old Belg. Gaden, to pleaſe, ſome people being never pleaſed, but when gadding about. Some alſo, by a Metaphor, take it from the Gad-fly;
 becauſe they firk up and down, like an Ox ſtung therewith. V. Gad-fly.

To Garr,
 for To Force,
 a word common in the North of England; from the Dan. Gior, to force.

A Gawk, or Cuckow,
 a word found in Somnerus; from the AS. Gaec, Geac, Gaec, a Cuckow;
 which ſee.

A Gherkin,
 ſo we call a pickled Cucumber; from the Teut. Gorcken, idem;
 ſimply, a Cucumber.

Gibberiſh, fooliſh diſcourſe; either q. d. Iabberiſh,
 from our word To Iabber;
 or from the Fr. G. Gaber, or the Ital. Gabbare, to put a trick on one; q. d. myſtical talk, that none underſtand, but thoſe that ſpeak it, Rogue's language, Pedlar's French. V. Iabber.

To Glow,
 from the AS. Gloƿan, the Belg. Gloeyen, or the Teut. Gluen, to ſhine; from hence, A Glow-worm;
 that is, a worm that gloweth, or ſhineth like a torch by night.

To Glow, or Glout;
 in Gouldman, To Stare.
 V. To Gloar.

                       Gog, He is A-Gog for it;
                        that is, he earneſtly, or greatly deſires

ſuch or ſuch a thing. It may (with a little variation of the ſence) be derived from the Fr. G. Gogues, great delight; or Se Goguer, to gratifie himſelf, to fare ſplendidly.

Graſs, from the AS. Graes, Gaers, the Belg. Graſs, Gars, or the Teut. Graſz, idem;
 whence the AS. Gaershop, in the Teut. and Eng. a Graſs-hopper.
 It may poſſibly come from the AS. Groƿan, to grow; q d. Groƿas, Groas, that which groweth all the fields over.

                       To Greet,
                        from the AS. Gretan,

the Belg. Groeten, Grueten, or the Teut. Grussen, to ſalute one; whence the AS. Gretan sendan, to ſend greeting.

A Grove,
 from the AS. Grove, Graef, idem: Or from our word to Grow; q. d. a Grow,
 or Growing of trees.

A Grove,
 a word uſed in Lincolnſhire for a grip, or ditch; from the Belg. Groeve, idem;
 v. Grave.

To Grunt,
 from the Teut. Gruntzen, the Fr. G. Grogner, the Ital. Grugnare, Grugnire, or the Dan. Grynter, idem;
 and all from the Lat. Grunnire, idem; and this from the ſound, by an Onomatopoeia.

An Hack,
 a word frequently uſed in Lincolnſhire; from the AS. Hacca, or the Belg. Heck, a door-barr, or place incloſed with bars; with us, an Hatch;
 which ſee.

An Hanger,
 from the Belg. Hangher, idem:
 Or 'tis ſo called from its hanging by one's ſide.

To Harry,
 from the Fr. G. Harier, to torment, or to Hare,
 which ſee above.

Hart of oak;
 not as many write it, Heart of oak;
 that is, the innermoſt part of an oak; but rather from the Teut. Harte, hardneſs; becauſe it is the moſt firm or hard part of an oak. V. Hard.

                       An Haſp, or Reel,
                        from the Fr. G. Haſpe, or the Teut. Haſpel,

a reel to wind yarn or thread on.

An Heap,
 from the AS. Heape, Hype, Fr. Th. Huffo, Hough, Teut. Hauff, or the Belg. Hoop, idem;
 this laſt from the Lat. Copia, plenty.

                       To Hold of the King, or a Lord: It may ſimply be drawn from our word, to Hold;
                        that is, to enjoy ſome Living, or Eſtate by the King's, or a Lord's donation: And for this reaſon our Law hath made uſe of the

words Tenant, and Tenement; both coming from the Lat. Teneo, to hold: Or from the AS. and Belg. Hold, faithful; or the Teut. Huldigen; as we ſay, to pay Homage to his Lord.

Horſe, from the AS. Hors, the Teut. Roſz or the Belg. Ros, idem;
 from hence our word Horſe-leech, (i. e.)
 a leech that doth faſten it ſelf upon horſes legs, and by ſucking away corrupted blood, helpeth them in ſeveral diſtempers. V. Leech.

To Hover,
 to fly about with wings ſtretched out at length, as a bird over her prey; from the AS. Heafian, to heave up; or from our word, to Cover;
 or from the Fr. G. Couver, or the Ital. Covare, to coure, as an hen doth upon her eggs.

To Humin,
 from the Belg. Hommelen, or the Teut. Hummen, idem;
 whence the Belg. Hommel, and Teut. Hammel, a drone; all feigned from the ſound

                       To Hunch,
                        from the Teut. Huſch,

a blow with the fiſt; and this not unlikely from the Lat. Ictus, a blow.

An Ilet,
 by contraction, an Eight;
 from the Fr. G. Iflette, or the Ital. Iſoletta, a little Iſland.

                       Imboſs, from the Ital. Imboſſare, to adorn with boſſes. V. Boſs:

From hence Imboſe'd-work;
                        which Higgin. calls Round-work.

An Ing,
 a word frequently uſed in Lincolnſhire, where it is put for a Meadow;
 and is derived from the Dan. Ing, a meadow.

The Hawk Ionks;
 V. To Iuke,
 or Iug.

To Iump,
 from the Belg. Gumpen, to leap, or dance; or perhaps, q. d. Gup, (i. e.) Go up,
 as he that jumps ſeems to do by the elevation of his body.

To Ken,
 for to Know,
 from the AS. Cennan, or the Belg. and Teut. Kennen, Kunnen, to know one. There is alſo found in the AS. Ic Can, and the Fr. Th. Ich Bekenno, I know him.

A Kid,
 or young goat, from the Dan. Kid, idem;
 and both from the Lat. Hoedus, a kid; which comes from the Heb. Gheddi, idem.

A Kitt,
 or milk-pale; from the Belg. Kitte, idem;
 both perhaps from the Lat. Catinus, a wooden diſh.

A Larder,
 from the Ital. Lardiero, Lardiera, a place wherein proviſion is laid up; this from the Lat. Lardum, q. d. Lardarium; from hence A Larderer,
 the Clerk of a Larder.

A Lay,
 or Song; from the AS. Ley, or the Teut. and Belg. Lied, idem;
 or poſſibly from the Ital. Ladetta, an hymn; all from La, a note in Muſick. It may alſo be derived from the AS. Leoð, the ſame; which comes from the AS. Leod, the Fr. Th. Luit, or the Teut. Leute, the common people; q. d. a rural ſonnet.

To Lay,
 in Lincolnſhire, To Lig;
 from the AS. Lecgan, the Belg. Leggen, or the Teut. Legen, idem,
 or place; whence the Dan. Vdlegger, as we ſay, To Lay out.

To Leap;
 in Lincolnſhire, To Lope;
 from the AS. Hleapian, idem; whence Hleap, Hlip, a leap, or jump; or from the Belg. Loopen, or the Teut. Lauffen, to run; from hence Leap-year, (i. e.)
 a year that leaps over, as it were, (i. e.) exceeds the reſt one day.

To Let,
 for To hinder; from the AS. Laetan, or the Belg. Letten, idem;
 all from the AS. Late, Laete, late.

A Libbard,
 from the Fr. G. Liepard, or the Belg. Libaerd, idem;
 both from the Lat. Leopardus, the ſame.

To Like,
 for To approve of, from the AS. Licean, Gelican, or the Fr. Th. Lichan, idem;
 or from the Noun Like, reſemblance.

                       To Link
                        or knit together, from the Fr. G. Lien, a chain;

whence Lier, to chain up; or rather, from the Teut. Gelenck, an iron link.

To Live,
 from the AS. Libban, Leofan, the Teut. Leben, or the Belg. Leven, idem;
 whence the AS. Liflic, lively, and Lif, the Run. Dan. and Dan. Liff, and the Teut. Liva, life.

A Load,
 from the AS. Lade, Hlade, or the Teut. Ladung, idem;
 whence the AS. Ladan, Hladian, and the Belg. and Teut. Laden, to load; all perhaps from the Fr. Th. Lithan, or the Teut. Leiden, to endure.

Lopper'd Milk,
 from the Teut. Lab, Laub, idem;
 clotter'd milk; theſe from Laben, to curdle, as milk kept too long in hot weather.

To Low,
 from the AS. Hloƿan, the Belg. Loeyer, or the Teut. Luyhen, idem;
 all from the ſound.

To Loyter,
 from the Belg. Loteren, or Leuteren, to delay, to linger; which may come from our Eng. Late, Later; (i. e.)
 not to perform a thing till it be late, or too late.

A Maid,
 from the AS. Maeden, the Belg. Maeght, Maegho, or the Teut. Magd, idem,
 a Virgin. Hence the AS. Maden-hade, a Maiden-head, or Virginity.

Monday, from the AS. Monandaeg, the Teut. Montag, or the Belg. Maendagh, idem.
 It may alſo be ſo called, q. Moon-day;
 and therefore in Latin rendred Dies Lunae, the Day of the Moon. v. Month, and Day.

                       A Moor,
                        incultivated ground;

from the AS. Mor, or the Belg. Moer, Moor, idem;
                        all perhaps from our word Mear, for Marſh.

To Mow, or Mew;
 as we ſay, To Mop and Mow,
 from the Fr. G. Faire la Moüe, to make a mouth, from Moüe, a wry mouth; which comes from the Teut. Manl, a mouth, or Maulen, to mouth at one.

To Open,
 from the AS. Openian, the Belg. Openen, the Teut. Olfaen, or the Dan. Obuer, idem;
 hence the Teut. Offen, and the Belg Open, open, manifeſt; as alſo Open Hertig, open hearted

To Parboil,
 from the Fr. G. Pourbouiller, to half boil; or, as Minſhew has it, Parum bullire, to boil a little; or rather, q. Part-boil,
 to boil in part.

                       Pelf, for temporal riches, from

the Fr. Nor. Peuffe, Fripery;
                        which ſee: Or rather, from the AS. Fela, Feo, much money, a fee.

To Perk,
 or Pirk up, q. d. To Pearch up;
 by a Metaphor taken from Hens ſtanding upon pearches.

To Piddle, or Pitle,
 to go about to do things of ſmall moment; from the Ital. Picolo, Picciolo, little; or our Eng. To Peddle;
 or the Fr. G. Petit, with us, Petty.

Pill'd, or Peel'd Garlick
 from our word, To Pill,
 or Peel; or à Pilis, from wool, or hair; for it is ſpoken properly of a Sheep, whoſe wool peeleth off; metaphorically, of a Man whoſe hair ſheds by reaſon of ſome diſeaſe, eſpecially the Venereal diſeaſe.

A Pipe,
 for a wine-veſſel, from the Hiſp. Pipa, or the Teut. Pippe, idem;
 or perhaps it is ſo called, becauſe it is hollow and long like a pipe.

                       A Plane,
                        from the Hiſp. Plana,

an inſtrument to make wood plain withal; both à Complanando, from making plain.

A Plough,
 from the Belg. Ploegh, or the Teut. Pflug, idem;
 whence Ploeghen, and Pflugen, to plow; all from the AS. Pluccian, to pluck; for the Oxen pluck the plough through the ground.

A Plum,
 from the AS. Plum, the Teut. Pflaume, or the Dan. Blumme, idem;
 all from the Lat. Prunum, the ſame.

A Plungeon, or Plongeon,
 from the word, To Plunge;
 a bird that often plungeth it ſelf in the water.

A Pound,
 from the AS. Pund, the Belg. Pond, or the Teut. Pfund, idem;
 all from the Lat. Pondo, a pound.

A Pulley
 from our word, To Pull,
 the Fr. G. Poulie, or the Ital. Poliga, idem.

A Race,
 from the Belg. Rannen, to run, q. d. Rauce;
 by ſtriking out n, for better ſounds ſake.

A Rake,
 from the AS. Race, the Belg. Raecke, or the Teut. Rachen, idem;
 whence Raeckelen, and Rechen, to rake.

                       To Raſe,
                        from the Fr. G. Raſer, Razer, to level with the ground, or Rayer, to blot out;

all from the Lat. Radere, to ſcrape.

To Ravel,
 from the Belg. Ravelen, to tangle: Hence To Vnravel,
 to diſ-entangle, to free from knots, to expound dark or myſtical expreſſions.

To Reek,
 for Smoak, from the AS. Recan, or the Teut. Rauchen, idem:
 Hence the AS. Rec, the Belg. Reuck, and the Teut. Rauch, ſmoak.

To Remain,
 from the old Fr. G. Remaindre, idem; this from the Lat. Remanere, to abide; from hence, A Remnant,
 and Remainder.

The Rode,
 from our word, To Ride,
 the Belg. Reede, or the the Fr. G. Rade, idem.

To Rove,
 from the Dan. Roffver, to rob; or the Fr. G. Roder, to ranſack. Where have you been Roving,
 v. Robbing.

To Scald,
 from the Fr. G. Eſchauder or the Belg. Schanden, idem;
 both from the It. Scaldare (i. e.) calidum facere, to make hot.

To Scold,
 from the Belg. Schelden; or the Teut. Schelten, idem,
 to chide.

A Scoop,
 from the Belg. Scoepe, idem,
 this from Schoepen, to ſcoop, or draw out.

A Screw,
 from the Bel Schroeve or the Teut. Schraubt, idem;
 whence the Belg. Schroeven, and Teut. Schrauben, to ſcrew up; yet moſt likely from the Fr. G. Eſcroüe, idem.

                       The Scut,
                        from the AS. Cƿyð,

or Belg. Kutte, idem;
                        this from our word Cut; it being ſo ſhort, as that part ſeems to be cut off.

A Seaſon,
 from the Fr. G Saiſon; the Ital. Stagione, or the Belg. Sayeſone idem;
 the It. from the Lat. Statio, a ſtation, to wit, of time.

A Seat,
 from the AS. Seotole, Dan. Saede, Teut. Sitz, or the Belg. Sate, idem;
 and all from the Lat. ſedes, ſedile, id.

To Shape,
 from the AS. Sceapan, the Belg. Schaepen, or the Fr. Th. Scaphon, idem;
 theſe from the Belg. Schaep, Schape, a ſhape, or form.

To Shave,
 from the AS. Scafan, Scaefan, the Belg. Schaven, or the Teut. Schaben, idem;
 all probably from the Lat. Scabere, to rub, or ſcrape.

To Shoot,
 from the AS. Sceotan, or the Belg. Schieten, idem;
 hence the Belg. Schentvry, ſhot-free; and the AS. Scoten, ſhot off: All perhaps from the Ital. Scuotere, or Scotere, or the Lat. Excutere, to ſhake off, with a little variation of the ſence.

Shovel, from the AS. Scofl, the Teut. Schauffel, or the Belg. Schoeffel, id.
 whence Schuyffelen, to ſhovel up; and all from the word, To Snow;
 which ſee.

To Sindge,
 from the AS. Saengan, the Belg. Senghen, or the Teut. Sengen, idem,
 to burn a little.

A Sled,
 or Sledge, from the Belg. Sledde, Slidde, the Teut. Schlitte; or the Dan. Slede, idem;
 and all from the word to Slide.

To Snort,
 or Snore, from the Belg. Snorcken, or the Teut. Snorchen, idem;
 and all from the ſound.

A Span,
 from the AS. Span, the Fr. G. Eſpan, the Ital. Spanna, or the Belg. and Teut. Spanne, idem;
 and all from the Belg. and Teut. Spannen, to extend, or ſtretch forth; and this Martin. derives from the Lat. Expandere, to ſpread out.

To Spare,
 from the AS. Sparian, the Fr. G. Eſpargner, the Ital. Sparagnare, or the Belg. Spaeren, idem;
 and all from the Lat. Parcere, to ſpare.

To Spew,
 from the AS. Spiƿan, the Teut. Speyen, or the Belg. Spouwen, idem;
 and all from the Lat. Spuo, idem.

A Spout,
 from the Teut. Sprutze, the ſame; whence Sprutzen, to ſprinkle: Or from the Belg. Spuyte, idem;
 whence Spuyten, to ſpout, or ſpin out.

To Stagger,
 from the Belg. Staggeren, idem;
 from hence alſo The Staggers,
 a diſeaſe among Horſes.

A Stair,
 from the AS. Staeger, or the Belg. Stegher, idem;
 theſe from the AS. Stigan, and the Belg. Steeghen, Stegghen, to aſcend by ſteps.

A Stake,
 or Wager, from the word To Stick;
 it being publickly ſtuck up, for the Winner's reward.

A Stalk,
 from the Teut. Stiel, or the Belg. Steel, Stele, idem;
 and theſe from the AS. Stigan, or the Teut. Steigen, to go up.

To Stew,
 from the Fr. G. Eſtuve, the Ital. Stufa, or the Dan. Stue, a hot houſe; and from hence a Stewes,
 or Bawdyhouſe.

Stock of a Tree,
 from the AS. Stocce, the Belg. and Teut. Stock, or the Fr. G. Eſtoc, idem; and from hence our words, Stock-blind,
 and Stock-ſtill.

To Summon,
 from the Fr. G. Semondre, idem; or q. d. Lat. Submonere, to warn, or give notice; from hence, A Summoner,
 and Summons, or Citation to appear before lawful Authority.

To Sweat,
 from the AS. Sƿetan, the Dan. Svaeder, or the Belg. Sweeten, idem:
 whence the AS. Sƿaette, the Dan. Sved, and the Belg. Sweet, ſweat.

A Teal,
 from the Teut. Teelingh, idem;
 this from Teeln, to procreate.

A Theif,
 from the AS. Ðeof, the Dan. Tiuff, or the Belg. Dief, idem;
 whence the AS. Ðeofian, to thieve, or ſteal; and Ðeofðe, theft. Write Thief.

To Think,
 from the AS. Ðincan, or the Belg. and Teut. Dencken, idem;
 hence the Fr. Th. Sin Thunkit, and the Belg. My Dunckt, methinks.

                       Timber, from the AS. Timbre, the Dan. Tommer, or

the Belg. Timber, Timmer, idem;
                        whence the AS. Atimbrian, to build with Timber.

To Tipple,
 from the Lat. Tipula, a Water-Spider; q. d. Tipulam agere, to play the Water-Spider; (i. e.) to be always drinking; or, from the Verb to Tipple;
 ſee Tip.

                       Together, from the AS. Togaeðere,

or the Belg. Te Gader, idem;
                        V. Gather.

