                       A Vein,
                        from the Fr. G. Veine, or the AS. Wegn, idem;

both from the Lat. Vena, idem.

A Viſe, or Skrew,
 from the Fr. G. Vis, a skrew; or the Belg. Vuſe, idem;
 whence Vuſen, to skrew up.

To Wade,
 from the AS. Wadan, the Belg. Waden, Waeden, or the Teut. Wadten, Watten, idem;
 all from the Lat. Vadare, to wade over; or Vadum, the ford of a river.

Wand, from the Dan. Vaand, idem;
 or from our word, to Wind;
 becauſe it is flexible.

A Cony-Warren,
 from the Fr. G. Garenne, or the Belg. Waerande, idem;
 all from Waeren, to have in cuſtody. V. Ward.

To Waſh,
 from the AS. Wascan, or the Belg. and Teut. Waſchen, idem;
 and hence Waſche, a Waſh or Waſhing.

                       Where, from the AS. Hƿaer,

the Run. Dan. Vif, or the Belg. Wiive, idem;
                        whence Wiiven, and the AS. Wifian, to marry a wife.

To Whiſper,
 from the Belg. Wiſperen, Wiſpelen, idem;
 all from the ſound.

A Wound,
 from the AS. Wund, the Belg. Wonde, or the Teut. Wunde, idem;
 from hence the AS. Wundian, the Belg. Wonden, and the Teut. Wunden, to wound.

                       A Wrinkle,
                        from the AS. Wrincle, the Dan. Rinckle, or the Belg. Wrinckel, idem;


whence the AS. Wrinclian, and the Belg. Wrinckelen, to wrinkle.

A Yard,
 from the AS. Geard, or the Dan. Gaard, idem;
 alſo a graſs plat.

Normanton Fields,
 in Northamptonſhire, corruptly for Dormanton Fields;
 from the AS. Dormanceaster, i. e. the old Town of Dormford. Somner writes it Dorm-ceaster, and derives it from the C. Br. Dor or Dwr, water, and withal placeth it in Huntingdonſhire.

ST. Tabb's, (i. e.) the Church of St. Ebba;
                         ſee St. Ebba
                         above.

The Vizes,
 in Wiltſh. perhaps from our word to Deviſe;
 which ſee in the Com. Names. q.d. a Caſtle built with much curioſity of Workmanſhip and Art.
